<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911125-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>911125-0055.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Safety-Kleen Corp.:   Lawsuit Filed by California   Is Settled for $1.3 Million</HL><DATE>11/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><CO>   SK</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Safety-Kleen Corp., Elgin, Ill., agreed to settle a suitfiled by the state of California, charging the company withviolations of the state and federal environmental laws.   The settlement calls for Safety-Kleen to pay $1.3 millionand participate in a statewide review of permit documentationfor its 16 California facilities. The company admitted nowrongdoing.</LP><TEXT>   As a result, the car and industrial cleaning concern saidit will take a charge that will reduce fourth-quarterearnings by about two cents a share. In the 1990 fourthquarter, Safety-Kleen earned $19.9 million, or 55 cents ashare.   In the suit, filed in April, the California Department ofHealth Services charged Safety-Kleen with violations rangingfrom the operation of unsafe trucks to unpermitted storage ofhazardous wastes. The company noted that the state dropped 24of its 89 allegations as part of the settlement.</TEXT></DOC>